<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; FREE COMPOSTING WORKSHOP PLANNED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATTHEW MOSK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Hoping to reduce yard waste and free up landfill space, Simi Valley officials 
will hold a free workshop Saturday to teach back-yard composting. 
</P>
<P>
 Instructors will explain a variety of methods to recycle plant material, 
including worm composting, special landscaping techniques and basic composting. 
</P>
<P>
 The event is open to any Simi Valley resident, said Joe Hreha, deputy director 
of environmental services. 
</P>
<P>
 "Anyone -- from a college student to someone who lives in an apartment to a 
person who lives on 20 acres -- can benefit from this," Hreha said. 
</P>
<P>
 The goal of the program is to help the city meet a state-required 25% cut in 
waste by 1995, Hreha said. Yard waste makes up 28% of the garbage sent from 
Simi Valley to local landfills. 
</P>
<P>
 Two composting workshops are held each year. 
</P>
<P>
 This event will take place from 10 a.m. to noon Saturday at Rancho Tapo 
Community Park. For more information, call 583-6874. MATTHEW MOSK 
</P>
</TEXT>
